nd various kinds of free verse, Miller’s poems celebrate communities both invented and real. Praise for Iron Wheel “Miller demonstrates that what Eliot said about reading a poem may be equally true of writing them: the best thing ‘is to be very, very intelligent’ and intelligence is not the same as erudition. Whether the world is made, found, or named, Miller offers an engaging portrait of things as they are.’’—David Orr, Poetry  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 0aAmerican literature. 0aAmerican poetry. 7aPOETRY / General.2bisacsh  apoetry, collection, literature, creative writing, contemporary, religion, spirituality, landscapes, seascapes, cityscapes, archeological digs, paintings, history, nature, environment, habitat, faith, belief, hope, emotion, urban, science, experiment, discovery, expedition, pursuit, desire, yearning, community, family, belonging, connection.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013z978311063538640uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226526157423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780226526157/original  a978-3-11-063538-6  University of Chicago Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_FAO  aGBV-deGruyter-alles